The '''Bearded Mary''' is an image from medieval [[iconography]] (from the time of the [[Carolingian dynasty]]) in which [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary, the mother of Jesus]], is depicted with a beard.<ref name="Bynum1984">{{cite book|last=Bynum|first=Caroline Walker|title=Jesus as Mother: Studies in the Spirituality of the High Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SRN0q7zfyiYC&pg=PA139|accessdate=7 April 2016|year=1984|publisher=U of California P|isbn=9780520052222|page=139}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Neusner|first=Jacob|title=Androgynous Judaism: masculine and feminine in the dual Torah|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5bXAAAAMAAJ|year=1993|publisher=Mercer UP|page=155}}</ref>

Carolyne Walker Bynum<ref name="Bynum1984"/> and Jeffrey Schnapp<ref name=Schapp>{{cite book|last=Schnapp|first=Jeffrey T.|editor=Marina S. Brownlee|others=Kevin Brownlee, Stephen G. Nichols|title=The New Medievalism|url=http://jeffreyschnapp.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/File0001.pdf|publisher=Johns Hopkins UP|location=Baltimore|pages=201–25|chapter=Dante's Sexual Solecisms: Gender and Genre in the ''Commedia''}}</ref> link the tradition to the (earlier) medieval idea that sexually chaste women could become like men, detailed by JoAnn McNamara, and even grow a beard (according to an account repeated by [[Gregory the Great]]).<ref>{{cite journal|last=McNamara|first=Jo Ann|year=1976|title=Sexual Equality and the Cult of Virginity in Early Christian Thought|journal=[[Feminist Studies]]|volume=3|issue=3/4|pages=145–58|jstor=3177733}}</ref> According to Schnapp, the Carolingian image suggests female cross-dressing can be "viewed as a sign of spiritual advancement", celebrating "the martial heroism of female martyr-saints such as Perpetua, Catherine, and Joan of Arc".<ref name=Schapp/>

