{{lowercase title}} {{Infobox website | name = Iversity | logo = Iversity neu.jpg | logocaption = | screenshot = | collapsible = | collapsetext = | caption = | url = {{URL|https://www.iversity.org/}} | commercial = Yes | type = [[Online education]] | registration = Required | language = English, German and Russian | owner = | author = [[Jonas Liepmann]] and [[Hannes Klöpper]] | num_users = 600.000+ (February 2015) | editor = | launch_date = {{Start date and age|2013|10|df=yes}} | alexa = | revenue = | current_status = Active | footnotes = }}
'''Iversity''' is a Berlin-based online education platform. Since October 2013, iversity has specialised in providing online courses and lectures in [[higher education]], specifically MOOCs ([[Massive Open Online Course]]s).<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/11/iversity-moocs-pivot/ Lomas, Natasha in Tech Crunch Online: ''Berlin-Based iversity Relaunches As MOOCs Platform, Sets Its Sights On Becoming The Coursera Of Europe''], 11 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.zeit.de/studium/uni-leben/2013-06/mooc-deutschland-iversity-vorlesungen-internet Schmidt, Marion in Die Zeit: ''Digitale Vorlesungshäppchen revolutionieren die Bildung''], 6 June 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.morgenpost.de/berlin-aktuell/startups/article114316168/Moocs-das-neue-Bildungsfernsehen-aus-der-Uni.html Stüber, Jürgen in Berliner Morgenpost: ''Moocs – das neue Bildungsfernsehen aus der Uni''] 11 March 2013</ref> Courses are free and open for anyone to enroll and participate.<ref>[http://www.arte.tv/sites/de/yourope-de/2014/05/27/iversity-die-wirklich-globale/, Arte: “iversity – die wirklich globale Universität”], 27 May 2014.</ref> Many of them are conducted in English or German, but also other languages.<ref>[http://venturevillage.eu/europe-mooc-berlin-iversity, Fowler, Nina in Venture Village: “Europe’s MOOC experiment accelerates in Berlin”], 15 October 2013.</ref> iversity cooperates with individual professors as well as different European universities.<ref>[http://www.cronacadiretta.i[t/dettaglio_notizia.php?idx=9&pg=28923, Blando, Stefano in Cronata Diretta: “E-learnig: L’università italiana in prima linea con i MOOC”], 22 January 2015.</ref><ref>[http://tribune.com.pk/story/736471/open-online-courses-ready-to-be-mooced/, Mulki, Muhammad Adil in Tribune Pakistan: “Online Courses: Ready to be MOOCed?], 20 July 2014.</ref><ref name="techcrunch.com">[https://techcrunch.com/2013/10/14/iversity-initial-students/, Lomas, Natasha in Tech Crunch: “Europe’s iversity Launches 1st MOOCs With 100k+ Students & Curriculum Of 24 Courses”], 14 October 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.uni-protokolle.de/nachrichten/id/289272/, Fachhochschule Köln: “UN und globales Hochschulnetzwerk bieten Online-Kurs zu Umweltkatastrophen und Klimawandel an”], 1 December 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.unicum.de/studienzeit/rund-ums-studium/allgemein/mooc-online-kurse-fuer-die-uni-von-zuhause/, Haberger, Denise/ von Kieter, Ann-Christin in UNICUM: “MOOC: Online-Kurse für die Uni von Zuhause”], 3 February 2014.</ref> Some of the courses were winners of the MOOC Production Fellowship held in early 2013.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/23/world/europe/european-universities-catch-the-online-wave.html?pagewanted=all&_r=2&, Schuetze, Christopher in New York Times: “European Universities Catch the Online Wave”], 22 September 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/unispiegel/studium/mooc-fellowship-stifterverband-und-iversity-kueren-mooc-konzepte-a-899937.html, Lupke-Narberhaus, Frauke in Der Spiegel Online: “Videos im Wettbewerb: Wo ist der beste Mooc?”], 22 June 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.heute.de/Digitaler-Campus-Das-Web-wird-zum-H%C3%B6rsaal-28069760.html, ZDF heute-Nachrichten: “Das Web wird zum Hörsaal”], 24 June 2013.</ref> iversity.org officially launched the MOOC platform online in October 2013<ref name="techcrunch.com"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/11/iversity-moocs-pivot/|title=Berlin-Based iversity Relaunches As MOOCs Platform, Sets Its Sights On Becoming The Coursera Of Europe – TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref>[http://edcetera.rafter.com/lessons-from-the-iversity-launch/, Winkler, Kirsten in: Edcetera: “Lessons from the iversity Launch”], 16 October 2013.</ref> and as of February 2015 has a user base of 600,000 online learners, enrolled in 63 courses offered by 41 partner universities. iversity is the only MOOC platform offering courses with [[European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System|ECTS]]-integration.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/unispiegel/studium/online-seminare-wie-moocs-bildung-und-hochschulen-veraendern-a-1000797.html, Kastner, Daniel in Spiegel Online: “Online-Seminare an Unis: Tablets raus, Massenarbeit!”], 5 November 2014.</ref><ref>[https://webmagazin.de/business/der-januar-lehrplan-von-iversity-ist-da-36820000, Pfeiffer, Lola in Webmagazin: “Der Januar-Lehrplan von iversity ist da”], 4 December 2014.</ref> iversity has branch offices in [[Bernau bei Berlin]], [[Germany]] and [[Berlin]].
== History == * Initial idea and development of a beta-version of the platform in 2008 by founder Jonas Liepmann.<ref>[http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/american-mooc-providers-face-international-competition/44637, Grossman, Sara in The Chronicle of Higher Education: “American MOOC Providers Face International Competition”], 5 July 2013.</ref> * This startup is said to have begun in 2011 and offered online collaboration tools for [[Learning Management|learning management]] with Hannes Klöpper as the co-founder and the second managing director.<ref name="Lomas">{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/09/online-learning-platform-iversity-gets-a-lifeline-from-holtzbrinck-media-group/|title=Online learning platform iversity gets a lifeline from Holtzbrinck media group|last=Lomas|first=Natasha|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-10-06|language=en}}</ref> * in 2012 iversity decided to become a European-based MOOC platform<ref>[http://www.wiredacademic.com/2013/07/5-questions-with-an-edtech-startup-hannes-klopper-of-berlin-based-mooc-provider-iversity/, Wired Academic: "5 Questions With An EdTech Startup: Hannes Klöpper of Berlin-based MOOC provider ‘iversity"], 4 July 2013.</ref> * Spring 2013 – iversity and the [[Stifterverband für die Deutsche Wissenschaft]] launched “The MOOC Production Fellowship” as a competition for online course concepts. A jury chose 10 of the best MOOC concepts out of more than 250 entries. The winners were each awarded €25,000 for the production of their courses.<ref>[http://venturevillage.eu/iversity-raises-funding, Fowler, Nina in Venture Village: “Online education platform iversity raises funding from T-Venture and new CEO”], 16 January 2013.</ref><ref>[https://iversity.org/en/pages/advisory-board, iversity: “Press Release: iversity creates Advisory Board”], 18 December 2013.</ref><ref>[http://netzwertig.com/2014/01/29/zwei-jahre-spaeter-15-heise-startups-aus-berlin-und-was-aus-ihnen-geworden-ist/, Weigert, Martin in Netzwertig: “Zwei Jahre später - heiße Startups aus Berlin und was aus ihnen geworden ist”], 29 January 2014.</ref> * In October 2013 iversity relaunched as a platform for online courses, initially with 10 courses and 115,000 registered users.<ref>[http://venturevillage.eu/iversity-stifterverband-mooc-fellowship, Fowler, Nina in Venture Village: "Professors, want to teach online? Berlin’s Iversity offers ten €25,000 MOOC fellowships"], 11 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/company-offers-cash-prizes-to-lure-professors-to-teach-moocs/43583?cid=wc Blumenstyk, Goldie in The Chronicle of Higher Education: "Company Offers Cash Prizes to Lure Professors to Teach MOOCs"], 25 April 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.edukwest.com/mooc-production-fellowship-announces-winners/, Winkler, Kirsten in Edukwest: "MOOC Production Fellowship announces Winners"], 10 June 2013.</ref> * In January 2014 online learners were able to take the first paid final, on-site exams, through which iversity earned its first revenues. * In October 2014, exactly one year since the relaunch, iversity's total funding reached over €5 million.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2014/02/19/iversity-500k-sign-ups/, Lomas, Natasha in Tech Crunch: “European Online Education Startup, iversity, Gets ~500k Course Sign-Ups In First 4-Months”], 19 February 2014.</ref><ref>[http://edukwest.eu/hedline-iversity-nears-500-000-enrollments/, Alexander, Kay in Edukwest: “iversity Nears 500.000 Enrollments”], 20 February 2014.</ref> * In August 2016, iversity secured a new investment from Holtzbrinck Digital,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gruenderszene.de/allgemein/holtzbrinck-digital-insolvenz-iversity|title=Holtzbrinck Digital investiert in strauchelndes Iversity|work=Gründerszene Magazin|access-date=2017-10-06|language=de}}</ref><ref name="Lomas"/> after filing for insolvency in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gruenderszene.de/allgemein/iversity-insolvenz|title=Iversity hat Insolvenz angemeldet – und will klein weitermachen|work=Gründerszene Magazin|access-date=2017-10-06|language=de}}</ref>
== Courses ==
[[Massive Open Online Course]]s (MOOCs) harness visual elements (lecture videos, animations, graphics), interactive elements (simulations) and written materials (scientific articles).<ref>[http://chronicle.com/blogs/conversation/2013/07/08/moocs-and-economic-reality/, Shirky, Clay in The Chronicle of Higher Education: "MOOCs and Economic Reality"], 8 July 2013.</ref><ref name="bohle">[http://www.scilogs.com/scientific_and_medical_libraries/librarians-and-the-era-of-the-mooc/, Bohle, Shannon in SciLogs: “Librarians and the Era of the MOOC”], 11 Mai 2013.</ref><ref>[http://newsok.com/first-massive-open-online-course-at-university-of-oklahoma-to-feature-graphic-novel/article/3759503?custom_click=lead_story_title, Price, Matthew in The Oklahoman: "First massive open online course at University of Oklahoma to feature graphic novel"], 1 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://chronicle.com/article/Dont-Call-Them-Textbooks/136835/, Young, Jeffrey R. in The Chronicle of Higher Education: "The Object Formerly Known as the Textbook"], 27 January 2013.</ref> All elements can be reviewed at any time. Instructor and course participants can interact with each other in discussion forums.<ref>[https://iversity.org/blog/user-interaction-learning-iversity-looks-like-iii/, iversity: “User Interaction: What learning at iversity looks like”], 13 October 2013.</ref> Instructors can use quizzes to get feedback on the learning progress of the course participants.<ref>[https://iversity.org/blog/learning-iversity-looks-like-breaking-90-minute-lecture/, iversity: "What learning at iversity looks like: Breaking down the 90 minute lecture"], 26 September 2013.</ref> Most iversity courses end with a final assessment or exam. Exams can be taken on-site, online as “[[proctor]]ed-exam” or in form of a final project that has to be handed in to the instructor.
Students at iversity.org can choose between different study paths, resulting in different certificates. “Statement of Participation” is free-of-charge, other certificates come with varying costs – depending on which level of certification the student chooses.<ref>[http://www.dailyfinance.com/2014/04/16/mooc-great-college-classes-free/, Kraft-Linder, Annalisa in Daily Finance: “MOOCs: What’s A Great College Class Worth When It’s Free?”], 16 April 2014.</ref><ref>[http://edcetera.rafter.com/verified-certificates-moocs-money-maker-or-anachronism/, Winkler, Kirsten in Edcetera: “Verified Certificates – MOOC’s Money Maker or Anachronism?”], 24 April 2014.</ref> Universities that offer a course at iversity have the option of offering European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System ([[European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System|ECTS]]) credits. This track allows students to receive credits from their course and apply them to their university studies. ECTS Credits can be used at any European Higher Education Institution. A certificate that awards ECTS credits is issued once the participant has passed an on-site or online proctored exam.<ref>[http://www.m-magazin.net/2014/03/virtuell-lernen-mit-moocs-das-prinzip-und-die-vorteile-von-massive-open-online-courses-37321.html, Strobel, Marisa in M-Magazin: “Virtuell lernen mit MOOCs”], 5 April 2014.</ref><ref>[https://iversity.org/en/pages/enrolments-revenue, iversity: “Online Education Platform iversity.org On The Road To Success”], 19 February 2014.</ref> Enrolment to courses is free, costs only apply when purchasing certificates.
For the production of courses, iversity collaborates with European universities and individual professors. Lecturers design their own MOOCs with technical support from iversity. iversity cooperates with institutions such as * [[Libera Università Internazionale degli Studi Sociali Guido Carli]] (LUISS) * [[RWTH Aachen]] * [[University of Buckingham]] * [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP) * [[Hertie School of Governance]] * [[European University Institute]] * [[University of Tubingen]] * [[University of Mainz]] * [[Reutlingen University]] (''Hochschule Reutlingen'' in German)
== Business Model == iversity earns revenue through the sale of certificates, which online learners receive after successfully completing courses on iversity.org thereby catering to all types of learners, among them working professionals who need to document their learning achievements and university students.<ref name="bohle" /> Some courses at iversity can be integrated into the student's [[diploma]] through the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS). iversity has raised more than €5 million in [[venture capital]]. The investors are T-Venture, bmp media investors, BFB Frühphasenfonds, Masoud Kamali, Westtech Ventures, CRALS, Peter Zühlsdorf and Kontor B45. The iversity Advisory board consists of Dr. Jörg Dräger and Prof. Édouard Husson.
